  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. The Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) of 1970\n- Requires financial institutions to report certain transactions\n- Mandates reporting of cash transactions over $10,000\n- Requires maintaining records of financial transactions\n\n2. The Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- Made money laundering a federal crime\n- Established criminal penalties for money laundering\n- Allowed government to prosecute individuals involved in laundering proceeds from specified unlawful activities\n\n3. The USA PATRIOT Act of 2001\n- Enhanced anti-money laundering provisions\n- Increased reporting requirements\n- Expanded financial institutions' obligations to detect and prevent money laundering\n\n4. The Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020\n- Updated and modernized existing anti-money laundering regulations\n- Expanded reporting requirements\n- Increased penalties for non-compliance\n\nAt the federal level, money laundering is primarily prosecuted under 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 and 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1957, which define specific money laundering offenses and establish criminal penalties.\n\nThese statutes work together to provide a comprehensive legal framework for preventing, detecting, and prosecuting money laundering activities.",
